T1  - Does a Parent–Subsidiary Structure Enhance Financing Flexibility?
AU  - VIJH, ANAND M.
Y1  - 2006/06/01
PY  - 2006
DA  - 2006/06/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.2006.00874.x
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
SP  - 1337
EP  - 1360
VL  - 61
IS  - 3
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.2006.00874.x
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - ABSTRACT I examine whether firms exploit a publicly traded parent?subsidiary structure to issue equity of the overvalued firm regardless of which firm needs funds, and whether this conveys opposite information about firm values. Using 90 subsidiary and 37 parent seasoned equity offering (SEO) announcements during 1981?2002, I document negative returns to issuers but insignificant returns to nonissuers in both samples, and insignificant changes in combined firm value and parent's nonsubsidiary equity value in subsidiary SEOs. Firms issue equity to meet their own financing needs. My evidence contrasts with previous studies and suggests that parent?subsidiary structures do not enhance financing flexibility.
ER  - 

