T1  - Uncovering the Risk–Return Relation in the Stock Market
AU  - GUO, HUI
AU  - WHITELAW, ROBERT F.
Y1  - 2006/06/01
PY  - 2006
DA  - 2006/06/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.2006.00877.x
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
SP  - 1433
EP  - 1463
VL  - 61
IS  - 3
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.2006.00877.x
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - ABSTRACT There is ongoing debate about the apparent weak or negative relation between risk (conditional variance) and expected returns in the aggregate stock market. We develop and estimate an empirical model based on the intertemporal capital asset pricing model (ICAPM) that separately identifies the two components of expected returns, namely, the risk component and the component due to the desire to hedge changes in investment opportunities. The estimated coefficient of relative risk aversion is positive, statistically significant, and reasonable in magnitude. However, expected returns are driven primarily by the hedge component. The omission of this component is partly responsible for the existing contradictory results.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Distance Constraints: The Limits of Foreign Lending in Poor Economies
AU  - MIAN, ATIF
Y1  - 2006/06/01
PY  - 2006
DA  - 2006/06/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.2006.00878.x
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
SP  - 1465
EP  - 1505
VL  - 61
IS  - 3
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.2006.00878.x
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - ABSTRACT How far does mobility of multinational banks solve problems of financial development? Using a panel of 80,000 loans over 7 years, I show that greater cultural and geographical distance between a foreign bank's headquarters and local branches leads it to further avoid lending to ?informationally difficult? yet fundamentally sound firms requiring relational contracting. Greater distance also makes them less likely to bilaterally renegotiate, and less successful at recovering defaults. Differences in bank size, legal institutions, risk preferences, or unobserved borrower heterogeneity cannot explain these results. These distance constraints can be large enough to permanently exclude certain sectors of the economy from financing by foreign banks.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Which Investors Fear Expropriation? Evidence from Investors' Portfolio Choices
AU  - GIANNETTI, MARIASSUNTA
AU  - SIMONOV, ANDREI
Y1  - 2006/06/01
PY  - 2006
DA  - 2006/06/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.2006.00879.x
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
SP  - 1507
EP  - 1547
VL  - 61
IS  - 3
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.2006.00879.x
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - ABSTRACT Using a data set that provides unprecedented detail on investors' stockholdings, we analyze whether investors take the quality of corporate governance into account when selecting stocks. We find that all categories of investors (domestic and foreign, institutional and small individual) who generally enjoy only security benefits are reluctant to invest in companies with weak corporate governance. In contrast, individuals connected with company insiders are more likely to invest in weak corporate governance companies. These findings suggest that it is important to distinguish between investors who enjoy private benefits or access private information, and investors who enjoy only security benefits.
